<subSubSection pageNumber="810" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="810">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">Note:</emphasis>
Blackwell &amp; al. (in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">Sida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
8: 161. 1979) referred to a specimen in LINN as the &quot;type specimen&quot; but did not distinguish between sheets 315.9, 315.18 and 315.32 (which are not part of a single gathering so Art. 9.15 does not apply). Castroviejo &amp; al. (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">Anales Jard. Bot. Madrid</emphasis>
43: 477. 1987) discussed these specimens in some detail and concluded that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1762" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Salsola" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sativa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">S. sativa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was a new species based in part on 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">S. souda</emphasis>
Loefl. (1758), which Linnaeus cited in the protologue of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1762" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Salsola" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sativa">S. sativa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Castroviejo &amp; al. argue that 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">S. souda</emphasis>
is merely an orthographic variant of 
<taxonomicName authority="L. (1753)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="soda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">S. soda</emphasis>
L. (1753)
</taxonomicName>
but that in 1762, Linnaeus recognised that 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Löfling’s">Loefling's</normalizedToken>
plant was distinct from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="soda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">soda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and gave it the name 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1762" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Salsola" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sativa">S. sativa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
In the absence of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="810">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Löfling">Loefling</normalizedToken>
123
</emphasis>
, they typified the name using 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Löfling’s">Loefling's</normalizedToken>
description, though this is now contrary to Art. 9, a type being either a specimen or an illustration.
</paragraph>
